@demographics
go-to: menu

**Demographic Groups**

**Unemployed:** For a long time a relatively minor group in America, it as been steadily rising ever since the 60's. Concerning mostly the Youth, minorities and out of jobs Blue collar worker, they tend to support whoever will give them a job and whoever won't take away their unemployement benefits. If their number rises high however, no amount of pandering to their position will convince them that you simply need more time as their uncertain future pushes them toward imediate solutions, not long term planning. (They are around 8% of the population at game start)

**Blue Collar:** What used to be the majority of the city population back when Gotham was an industrial Hub. As the town as shifted away from the power of industry, their numbers have been dwindling and so have their welfare. While once Reliable Blue Voters, Union Busting and De-industrialization have since shifted them the center and now are sensitive to populist rhetoric and whichever support their jobs the most. They represent 30% of the population yet have low participation rate in elections. 

**Business Owners:** From the Pizza restaurants, self employed to market chains owners, a significant part of the population of Gotham are what could be called the old middle class or "petty bourgeoisie". Possessing their own Capital of production as well as societal and economic concerns that are in contradiction to much of the working class, they tend to be much more conservative no matter their actual economic well being. While representing only 10 to 15% of the population, they are very reliable voters for the republican party.

**White Collar:** As the economics of the city shift away from manual labor in factories toward skyscrappers of glass filled with offices, the population of the city as gained a vast number of jobs pertaining to the new middle Class. Under Salaries much like Blue Collar workers but generally much better off and tending to have higher level of education, this part of the population tend to lean toward liberalism which generally see them lean toward the democratic party though a vast part of them remain Republican. As 30% of the population, they represent another active block of voters which while generally unable to change elections as they are always voting, they grant parties strong bases of support for both parties.

**Blacks:** Up until recently, the largest minority of voters of the City came from the Black Community. While indivually part of every other class previously mentionned, the Black population as tended to vote as a united block toward issues favoring their enfranchisement. As such, they have been extremely reliable Democratic voters. However, they have also been known to refuse to vote for any candidate if neither represent their values with enough strength, a phenomenon that as become more frequent as of late. They represent around 15% of the population in the city.

**Latinos:** The fastest growing minority of the city and also the least politically active. While skewing toward the left on economic issues, as they skew toward the right on social ones, they have become a generally uninvolved part of the political spectrum which usually tilts democrat but remain in search of candidates that would better represent their issues. Profoundly anti-establishment, they will flock to populist candidate or Candidates that make facing the issues they have part of their platform. They represent around 15% of the population

